                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                                        <date>June 29, 5608</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">My dear Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">I can very readily excuse<lb/> you for what I
                                        began to think was a little piece<lb/> of neglect on your
                                        part in delaying to write me a long<lb/> note that I know
                                        what was the cause one which I<lb/> regalled much to hear,!
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> you are not to <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        yourself for a <add>Hebrew</add> It is true that in no
                                        period<lb/> of their existence nationally, did our brethren
                                        stand in greater<lb/> need of instruction and of being
                                        aroused to a due sense of their<lb/> duty than now, and
                                        therefore, I still continue to say <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        but do not let your health suffer by so doing, why not
                                        take<lb/> a little recreation? Why not take a trip into
                                                  <placeName>Montreal</placeName> this summer?<lb/>
                                        Do you wait for a formal invitation? Here is one for you
                                        there<lb/> “The <persName>Rev Abraham deSola</persName> sees
                                        also many other friends will be most<lb/> happy to see the
                                                  <persName>Rev Isaac Leeser</persName> in
                                                  <placeName>Montreal</placeName> during the
                                        present<lb/> summer, when, should the <persName>Rev. I
                                                  L.</persName> determine upon coming, they<lb/>
                                        will <sic>will</sic> endeavor to make the arrangements
                                        which<lb/> will enable him to pass his time as pleasurably
                                        as it is possible<lb/> to do in so outlandish a place ”
                                        Please excuse the pink edged<lb/> not paper, but seriously,
                                        dear Friend, I think that a trip to<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Canada</placeName> would do you much good, and I
                                        shall be delighted to see<lb/> you, to find you a room, to
                                        show you my books, and (probably)<lb/> to grovel with you
                                        over their contents.</p>
                              <p>Receive my best thanks for your kindness in inserting the long<lb/>
                                        notice of my lecture, I have not the least doubt as to the
                                        party<lb/> who sent it, He <hi rend="underline">is</hi> an
                                        esteemed friend of mine, and one I believe<lb/> with whom
                                        you are also well acquainted but as you don't<lb/> mention
                                        names I shall not.</p>
                              <p>You misunderstand me as regards the <add>Hebrew</add>. My object
                                        was<lb/> to publish it in the same way as
                                                  <persName>English's</persName> book was
                                        republished<lb/> in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName> It would
                                        have been an anonymous publication—<lb/> this I think I
                                        neglected to tell you, as I write in haste, My<lb/> object
                                        was further, to <add>?</add> from you as the person
                                        most<lb/> able to inform me, whether there were reading
                                        Israelites enough<lb/> in <placeName>America</placeName> to
                                        pay for the printing of the book, not to<lb/> make it a
                                        course of profit, that of course I would not expect.<lb/> I
                                        know as well as you (excuse nay indulgence) that
                                        neither<lb/> pudding nor fame was to be derived from it, but
                                        such</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>is my estimation of the work, that I think it would do<lb/> a great
                                        deal of good, were it generally known. I did not at all<lb/>
                                        expect, my dear Friend, that you would gather
                                        subscriptions<lb/> To repeat your own words “That figure is
                                        out of the question.”<lb/> I only <add>?</add> open for what
                                        you have readily given me<lb/> your advise, and
                                        co-operation. Many thanks for your<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> as to fishing in troubled waters. I am well
                                        convinced<lb/> I can assure you of the value &amp; truth of
                                        what you say, but in<lb/> case of being attacked by some of
                                        our christian friends (which I<lb/> think would be unlikely,
                                        the publication being anonymous<lb/> I would always be in
                                        possession of the <add>?</add> provide) by some<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> of controversial writers on our side the
                                        auction so that<lb/> at all events I should have the means
                                        if not the capability to<lb/> give them drubbing for
                                        drubbing. I have no wish however as<lb/> I know my own
                                        (insufficiency, to enter into controversial<lb/>
                                        disputation, and if I desired to give to the public some of
                                        my<lb/> translations <hi rend="underline">as my own</hi> and
                                        which I have by me I<lb/> certainly would not choose the
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> but rather my <hi
                                                  rend="underline">humble</hi><lb/> renderings of
                                        our <hi rend="underline">Rabbinical</hi> writers, I am more
                                        attached to them<lb/> than to Lituanian<add>?</add>
                                                  Caraibes<add>?</add> and always was so. Tell me,
                                        how<lb/> would you like to receive some of these
                                        translations for<lb/> publication in the Occident, and then,
                                        before the matter is distributed<lb/> print off
                                                  <sic>seperately</sic>, say 500 copies of them I
                                        paying the difference<lb/> and receiving the books or you
                                                  <sic>takeing</sic> those with me in the
                                        profits<lb/> and leaving the proportionate expense. The
                                        difference could not<lb/> be very great as there would be
                                        but little alteration to be<lb/> made in the matter before
                                        it is distributed and merely<lb/> the expense of paper &amp;
                                        press work. I am sure I could dispose<lb/> of many in
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName>
                                        <add>?</add>. I have promised to<lb/> contribute to the
                                        Occident and I don't know why one should<lb/> not derive
                                        mutual benefit from the course first proposed—</p>
                              <p>Please understand me, I do not mean that the <add>Hebrew</add>
                                        should<lb/> so appear, but smaller works such as the
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                                        <add>Hebrew</add> translations of<lb/> which I have made
                                        although not completed. <sic>Dont</sic> think<lb/> either
                                        that it is a mania for printing which leads me<lb/> to
                                        propose this but receive it as a casual thought the<lb/>
                                        value and practicability of which you are yourself to<lb/>
                                        determine in your next communication. But let me</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>remind you, that selections from the writings of
                                                  <persName>Maimonides</persName> were<lb/>
                                        published by <persName>Bernard</persName>, though not those
                                        which I have.<lb/> The book sold well among christians and
                                        even among Jews<lb/> no doubt because the author was a
                                                  chestiuvuad<add>?</add>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">You will ere this have received the first
                                                  <sic>instalment</sic> of my<lb/> promised article
                                        on the settlement of the Jews in
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName>. It<lb/> is a dark
                                        subject and perhaps you and your readers may say<lb/> a
                                        profitable one, but it is one which I was compelled to
                                        write<lb/> in my lecture on the Jews of
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName> and you have it in
                                                  <add>?</add><lb/> form. The Sermon or the
                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> you will perceive is<lb/> one of
                                        a series therefore if you have not already published<lb/> it
                                        and will press it back a month or so, inducting the<lb/>
                                        Enquiry “instead, I will send you one or two others on
                                        the<lb/> same subject. With the 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi>
                                        <sic>instalment</sic> of the “Enquiry” some<lb/> you
                                                  <sic>you</sic> will have enough of my scribbles
                                        has at least<lb/> 3 Occidents to come i.e. If you reckon the
                                        Sermon and<lb/> publish the <sic><hi rend="underline"
                                                  >instalments</hi></sic> separately if you print
                                        them<lb/> together pray let me know for I am quite in the
                                        dark as to your<lb/> proceedings as we get the Occidents so
                                        late here, but not<lb/> here only. Why should <persName>Mrs
                                                  Joel</persName> of <placeName>London</placeName>
                                        say she had not<lb/> received any for the last 3 months.
                                        Prenez garde, Monsieur le<lb/> Redacteur! Thanks for the
                                                  aptra<add>?</add> she sent me. I shall<lb/> (in
                                        return/) expect the same favor every time any papers of<lb/>
                                        mine may be inserted. I send you a report (or rather a<lb/>
                                        digest of one since it would be inconvenient to send so
                                        much<lb/> paper, of the first years operations of our
                                        society. If you<lb/>
                                        <sic>dont</sic> feel inclined to publish all the
                                                  <add>?</add> names<lb/> it contains, pray do not,
                                        but just say 'an those will that<lb/> “there follow the
                                        names” The committees wanted to give the people enough<lb/>
                                        but I think the feel stated should be quite sufficient. I am
                                        quite pleased with <persName>Mrs Jacob<lb/>
                                                  Joseph</persName>, lately arrived among us, and
                                        indeed so<lb/> are all here. She is extremely amiable and
                                        intelligent<lb/> I regret much that I have not been able to
                                        see her<lb/> as often as I could wish. Preuis<add>?</add> le
                                        temps viendra<lb/> Pray do not allow so long &amp; time to
                                        intervene</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>before writing again By the way, your letter is dated<lb/>
                                        <date>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> June</date> and I did not
                                        receive it till the <date>27<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                                        with<lb/> the Occidents. Stand when you write, write
                                        fully.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Now dear friend farewell for the present<lb/> with
                                        earnest prayers for your perfect health and<lb/> general
                                        welfare believe me</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">Very truly yours</p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>
                                                  <sic>1 Pres deVille Plase</sic>
                                        </placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">
                                        <persName role="author">Abraham deSola</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>A lady (<persName>Miss Miriam Belisario</persName>) formerly a
                                        pupil<lb/> of mine has lately published a Hebrew &amp;
                                        English <add>?</add><lb/> advertised in the day to Jewish
                                        papers as <add>Hebrew</add> &amp; he<lb/>she wishes that she
                                        has sent me a copy, but<lb/> having entrusted it to some
                                        person to <add>?</add> me, who<lb/> was going out to
                                                  <placeName>Canada</placeName> I have not yet seen
                                        it.<lb/> I would otherwise have written a review (for the
                                        sake of<lb/> old acquaintanceship) for the Occident. If you
                                        feel<lb/> disposed to resign the post of honor, or
                                                  <sic>dont</sic> intend<lb/> writing one, pray send
                                        me the books per first<lb/> opportunity and I will endeavor
                                        to do the<lb/> needful.</p>
